Merger with complements and bundling: The case of Claro, Colombia

JS VÃ©lez

October 18, 2015

In this document I look at the quality and price effects of a merger of firms that produced complementary goods prior to the merger.

Timeline

In 2012 two events shook Colombiaâs telecommunications market. The events involved some of Colombiaâs largest companies. First, regulators authorized Telefonica, the second largest cellphone carrier, to take control of Coltel, a down-on-his-luck giant of phone services that had started providing broadband recently. Second, Comcel and Telmex were merged under the brand Claro (Comcel was a the time the countryâs largest cellphone carrier and Telmex was the second Internet service provider). Despite the similarities, the two mergers had different motivations. I focus on the latter (Comcel-Telmex merger).

Policies

The following policies were enacted close to the dates of the the mergers. All of them aimed to increase the demand for Internet in low income households.

Decree 2917 (of 2011)
Starting on September 2011 (and ending in September 2013) 0% tariff on computer imports. The tariff used to be 5%.

Law 1430 (of 2010, article 11)
No VAT for Internet subscribers in strata 1, 2 and 3 starting in January 2013.

Law 1450 (of 2011, article 55)
Internet services are subsidized for strata 1 and 2 (the poorer). It started on September 2012 and the government had spent $20 million by March 2013.

If the provision of broadband exhibits economies of scale, this policies may cause an increase in the speeds offered. The policies affected only certain types of plans which allows me to remove the effect of the policies. The merger and the policies overlapped but they didnât take place contemporarily.

The graphs below depict the evolution of download speeds for the main broaband providers in Colombias 4 largest cities.

Mobile internet also shows the effect of the merger. Before the merger Comcelâs trafic was below Telefonicaâs. After the merger Comcel (merged with Telmex) overtook Telefonica. The effect must have been due exclusively to the increase capacity after having access to Telmexâs networks since other mobile uses like text messages didnât change (graph below).

It seems as if after the merger markets where Telmexâs kept experiencing increases in prices but at a lower rate than markets whithout Telmex.

Theory

The literature about mergers with complements is sparse (Choi, 2008; Anderson et al., 2010; Flores and Moner, 2011). Luckily the few papers that model mergers of firms producing complementary goods arrive at similar conclusions: the merging firms will charge for the bundle a price that is lower than the sum of prices of the components of bundle prior to the merger.
